00:23:03,269 --> 00:23:04,130
and I don't feel bad about it.

578
00:23:05,867 --> 00:23:10,430
Um, another problem with the kidnapping scene is that it's not the archetypal kidnapping scene.

579
00:23:10,470 --> 00:23:13,833
Like, there's this weird replacement victim concept, and there's a lot of scene changes.

580
00:23:13,853 --> 00:23:18,836
Um, and being a deviation from the expected norm is also true of, like, the secret society

581
00:23:18,856 --> 00:23:21,858
and how they work, and the butler being in the family portrait.

582
00:23:22,418 --> 00:23:25,040
Um, I think archetypes can be great for helping the player understand,

583
00:23:25,120 --> 00:23:28,102
but I use them really sparingly because I believe that cliches are lame.

584
00:23:28,122 --> 00:23:30,623
That's a technical word for it.

585
00:23:31,651 --> 00:23:35,352
Since we're making a list, here are some things I've had a hard time depicting with environmental storytelling.

586
00:23:35,412 --> 00:23:37,532
We've already mentioned timelines and causality.

587
00:23:37,892 --> 00:23:41,594
This tends to extend to character motivations, like the butler's cache of treasures.

588
00:23:41,974 --> 00:23:44,214
Why is he hiding them inside the house?

589
00:23:44,374 --> 00:23:46,735
Is his plan to come back and steal them later or something?

590
00:23:47,815 --> 00:23:50,736
Things that are missing are hard to convey because they're not on screen.

591
00:23:51,216 --> 00:23:54,197
So this perch is missing a mechanical blackbird that's supposed to be there,

592
00:23:54,237 --> 00:23:57,578
but without seeing the bird, players thought it might be a handle or a lever.

593
00:23:58,035 --> 00:23:59,895
So we actually had to just like depict the bird

594
00:24:00,015 --> 00:24:02,376
on its perch like very nearby in the same scene.

595
00:24:03,677 --> 00:24:05,197
And those two points together explain

596
00:24:05,217 --> 00:24:07,038
a recurring problem in the Spider games.

597
00:24:07,738 --> 00:24:08,978
These places are always abandoned,

598
00:24:09,018 --> 00:24:11,219
but unless they literally put the corpse in the game,

599
00:24:11,299 --> 00:24:13,320
no player has any idea where all the characters went.

600
00:24:13,440 --> 00:24:15,760
So for example, we saw that T-Brice climbed out

601
00:24:15,780 --> 00:24:17,561
that basement window, but we don't know for sure

602
00:24:17,661 --> 00:24:19,222
if that was his final appearance in the story.

603
00:24:21,124 --> 00:24:23,746
There's a lot of things I regret about Spider 2.

604
00:24:24,286 --> 00:24:26,268
I think Spider 1's hooks were hookier.

605
00:24:26,348 --> 00:24:28,189
Spider 2 takes a little while to get going.

606
00:24:29,110 --> 00:24:31,012
Spider 2 is too close to Spider 1,

607
00:24:31,352 --> 00:24:32,593
which is part of that problem.

608
00:24:32,673 --> 00:24:34,494
Like, they both take place in abandoned mansions,

609
00:24:34,535 --> 00:24:36,296
and so I had already used my best material,

610
00:24:36,796 --> 00:24:39,118
in particular, to establish that it's an abandoned mansion.

611
00:24:39,919 --> 00:24:41,240
Spider 2 is kind of a lot.

612
00:24:41,300 --> 00:24:42,961
It's really stuffed full of ideas.

613
00:24:43,001 --> 00:24:44,262
It's a little bit of an overreach.

614
00:24:45,904 --> 00:24:47,845
Probably fewer ideas with more stage time each

